{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2017}} {{Use Indian English|date=September 2017}} {{Infobox person | name = Neel Kamal Puri | image = Neel Kamal Puri.jpg | caption = In Ludhiana, September 2006 | birth_name = | othername = Neelu | occupation = Writer | lives in = Chandigarh | birth_date = {{Birth date|df=yes|1956|02|14}} | birth_place = [[Ludhiana]], [[Punjab, India]] | education = [[Panjab University, Chandigarh]] | spouse = Asit Jolly }}
'''Neelkamal Puri''' (born 1956) is an Indian author, columnist and a college teacher.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.penguinbooksindia.com/en/content/neel-kamal-puri |title=Neel Kamal Puri |publisher=Penguin Books India |date= |accessdate=2013-12-03}}</ref> Born in [[Ludhiana]], [[Punjab, India|Punjab]], she grew up in the erstwhile princely state of [[Patiala]], where she did her schooling from the Yadavindra Public School. Since 1979, she has worked as a lecturer in English Literature at different colleges in Patiala and Chandigarh. She is currently teaching Literature and Media Studies at the Government College for Girls, [[Chandigarh]].
==Books== Neelkamal Puri has written two novels, ''The Patiala Quartet'' published by Penguin India<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.penguinbooksindia.com/en/content/patiala-quartet |title=Patiala Quartet |publisher=Penguin Books India |date=2006-01-01 |accessdate=2013-12-03}}</ref> and ''Remember to Forget'' published by Rupa Publications.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rupapublications.co.in/authors/neel-kamal-puri |title=Neel Kamal Puri |publisher=Rupa Publications |date= |accessdate=2013-12-03 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130816103333/http://rupapublications.co.in/authors/neel-kamal-puri |archivedate=16 August 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Noted writer [[Khushwant Singh]] described ''The Patiala Quartet'' as among the best works of English fiction written by a Punjabi.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2006/20060114/saturday/above.htm |title=The Tribune - Magazine section - Saturday Extra |publisher=Tribuneindia.com |date=2006-01-14 |accessdate=2013-12-03}}</ref> After these stories based in cities she was born in and the city she grew up in, Neelkamal Puri is working next on a collection of short stories ''Theka Tales''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/punjabs-victory-over-history/1/251178.html |title=Punjab's victory over history : Simply Punjabi - India Today |publisher=Indiatoday.intoday.in |date=2013-02-21 |accessdate=2013-12-03}}</ref>
